{"title_page": "Spanish Steps (Washington, D.C.)", "text_new": "{{Infobox urban feature\n|name=Decatur Terrace\n|image_place=Spanish Steps - Kalorama.JPG\n|pushpin_map=United States Washington, D.C.\n|pushpin_map_caption= Location of Spanish Steps in Washington DC\n|location=22nd Street NW just south of S Street NW\n|address2=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|38.91372|-77.04879|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-DC|display=inline,title}}\n|place_type=[[Stairs|Public stairs]]\n|owner=\n|designer= Robert E. Cook\n|open=1911\n|dedicated_to=\n|steps=\n}}\n\n'''Decatur Terrace''', affectionately known as the '''Spanish Steps''', is a [[Terrace garden|terrace]] in the [[Kalorama, Washington, D.C.|Kalorama]] neighborhood of [[Washington, D.C.]], located on 22nd Street NW, connecting Decatur Place NW and S Street NW. Formally named '''Decatur Terrace Steps and Fountain''', the nickname is a reference to the [[Spanish Steps]] in [[Rome]]. Washington's Spanish Steps are listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as a contributing feature in the [[Kalorama (Washington, D.C.)|Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District]], designated in 1989.\n\n== History ==\nDecatur Terrace was built in 1911.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://sheridankaloramacallbox.org/sheridan-kalorama/spanish-steps-preservation-project.html|title=Spanish Steps Preservation Project|last=|first=|date=|website=Sheridan-Kalorama Call Box Restoration Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=89001743}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District|author=Emily Hotaling Eig and Julie Mueller, Traceries|date=1989}}</ref> The Washington DC Municipal Office of Public Works and Grounds determined that the steep [[escarpment]] made construction of a street impractical, as it would require destroying destroying adjacent building sites. A ramp would have been difficult for carriages and automobiles and uncomfortable for pedestrians.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wrenn|first=Tony|title=Walking Tours: Washington, D.C.|publisher=Preservation Press, National Trust for Historic Preservation|year=1975|isbn=|location=Washington, DC|pages=115}}</ref> In 1905, District Commissioners decided to inaugurate a \"park improvement idea\" in lieu of a driveway.<ref name=\":2\">\"[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/1905-06-11/ed-1/seq-9/ Steps and Flowers Instead of Steep Drive].\" ''The Washington Times'', June 11, 1905. p. 9.</ref> Property along the [[Right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]] was deeded to the city for the construction of steps and an adjacent park. Decatur Terrace is Washington's only example of a staircase constructed on land dedicated to a street.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe steps and fountain were designed by local architect [[Robert Edwin Cook|Robert E. Cook]] for the Municipal Office of Public Works.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The stone steps were designed following [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] precepts, reflecting the aesthetic preferences made popular in Washington, D.C. by the [[City Beautiful movement]]. \n\nThe broad staircase has four levels. It is widest at its low, southern terminus near Decatur Place, transitioning upwards towards a shallow brick terrace and a second tier of stairs bordered by planting beds. Twin [[Baluster|balustrade]]-lined steps curve around an oval-shaped basin before connecting to a broad terrace on S Street. A granite lion-head fountain is located in the basin at the top of the steps.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The area is lined with a mix of magnolias, eastern red cedars, oaks, and other flowering trees. To the east of the Spanish Steps, a brick and stone retaining wall with balustrade creates and defines a formal side garden for the Codman-Davis House.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDue to severe erosion and a car collision that destroyed the original stone [[Baluster|balustrade]] and fountain, the steps and landscape were restored in 1999.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation|url=http://tclf.org/landscapes/spanish-steps|title=Spanish Steps}}</ref>\n\n== Construction ==\nBids for construction of Decatur Terrace opened in June 1905.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1905-06-04/ed-1/seq-5/#date1=1905&index=1&rows=20&words=Decatur+steps&searchType=basic&sequence=0&state=District+of+Columbia&date2=1912&proxtext=decatur+steps&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Sealed Bids Opened|date=June 4, 1905|work=Washington Evening Star|access-date=April 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> <gallery>\nFile:Spanish Steps (Washington, D.C.).JPG |Lion-head fountain\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Spanish Steps (Washington, D.C.)}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Stairways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Stairways on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n\n{{WashingtonDC-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox urban feature\n|name=Decatur Terrace\n|image_place=Spanish Steps - Kalorama.JPG\n|pushpin_map=United States Washington, D.C.\n|pushpin_map_caption= Location of Spanish Steps in Washington DC\n|location=22nd Street NW just south of S Street NW\n|address2=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|38.91372|-77.04879|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-DC|display=inline,title}}\n|place_type=[[Stairs|Public stairs]]\n|owner=\n|designer= Robert E. Cook\n|open=1911\n|dedicated_to=\n|steps=\n}}\n\n'''Decatur Terrace''', affectionately known as the '''Spanish Steps''', is a [[Terrace garden|terrace]] in the [[Kalorama, Washington, D.C.|Kalorama]] neighborhood of [[Washington, D.C.]], located on 22nd Street NW, connecting Decatur Place NW and S Street NW. Formally named '''Decatur Terrace Steps and Fountain''', the nickname is a reference to the [[Spanish Steps]] in [[Rome]]. Washington's Spanish Steps are listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]] as a contributing feature in the [[Kalorama (Washington, D.C.)|Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District]], designated in 1989.\n\n== History ==\nDecatur Terrace was built in 1911.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://sheridankaloramacallbox.org/sheridan-kalorama/spanish-steps-preservation-project.html|title=Spanish Steps Preservation Project|last=|first=|date=|website=Sheridan-Kalorama Call Box Restoration Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=89001743}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Sheridan-Kalorama Historic District|author=Emily Hotaling Eig and Julie Mueller, Traceries|date=1989}}</ref> The Washington DC Municipal Office of Public Works and Grounds determined that the steep [[escarpment]] made construction of a street impractical, as it would require destroying destroying adjacent building sites. A ramp would have been difficult for carriages and automobiles and uncomfortable for pedestrians.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wrenn|first=Tony|title=Walking Tours: Washington, D.C.|publisher=Preservation Press, National Trust for Historic Preservation|year=1975|isbn=|location=Washington, DC|pages=115}}</ref> In 1905, District Commissioners decided to inaugurate a \"park improvement idea\" in lieu of a driveway.<ref name=\":2\">\"[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/1905-06-11/ed-1/seq-9/ Steps and Flowers Instead of Steep Drive].\" ''The Washington Times'', June 11, 1905. p. 9.</ref> Property along the [[Right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]] was deeded to the city for the construction of steps and an adjacent park. Decatur Terrace is Washington's only example of a staircase constructed on land dedicated to a street.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe steps and fountain were designed by local architect Robert E. Cook for the Municipal Office of Public Works.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The stone steps were designed following [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] precepts, reflecting the aesthetic preferences made popular in Washington, D.C. by the [[City Beautiful movement]]. \n\nThe broad staircase has four levels. It is widest at its low, southern terminus near Decatur Place, transitioning upwards towards a shallow brick terrace and a second tier of stairs bordered by planting beds. Twin [[Baluster|balustrade]]-lined steps curve around an oval-shaped basin before connecting to a broad terrace on S Street. A granite lion-head fountain is located in the basin at the top of the steps.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The area is lined with a mix of magnolias, eastern red cedars, oaks, and other flowering trees. To the east of the Spanish Steps, a brick and stone retaining wall with balustrade creates and defines a formal side garden for the Codman-Davis House.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDue to severe erosion and a car collision that destroyed the original stone [[Baluster|balustrade]] and fountain, the steps and landscape were restored in 1999.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|website=The Cultural Landscape Foundation|url=http://tclf.org/landscapes/spanish-steps|title=Spanish Steps}}</ref>\n\n== Construction ==\nBids for construction of Decatur Terrace opened in June 1905.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1905-06-04/ed-1/seq-5/#date1=1905&index=1&rows=20&words=Decatur+steps&searchType=basic&sequence=0&state=District+of+Columbia&date2=1912&proxtext=decatur+steps&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Sealed Bids Opened|date=June 4, 1905|work=Washington Evening Star|access-date=April 13, 2020|url-statu